# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: css-grid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] CSS grid layout contains rules that control what happens when you create a grid and do not explicitly place some or all of the child items within the grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] When you don't need explicit control over content placement, this "auto-placement" is the simplest way of creating a grid for a set of items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] If you don't give the items placement information, they automatically position themselves on the grid, placing one grid item in each grid cell.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] As you can see with the above example, if you create a grid without placing any items, the child items will lay themselves out, with one grid item in each grid cell in source-code order.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The default flow is to arrange items by row.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Grid will lay an item out into each cell of the first row.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] If you have created additional rows using the `grid-template-rows` property, then grid will continue placing items in these rows.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] If the grid does not have enough rows in the explicit grid to place all of the items new *implicit* rows will be created.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The default for automatically created rows in the implicit grid is for them to be *auto-sized*.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] This means that they will size themselves to contain the content added to them without causing an overflow.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The size of these rows can be controlled using the property `grid-auto-rows` property.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The `minmax()` function enables creating rows that have a minimum size, and can grow to fit content as needed when set as the `grid-auto-rows` value.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The following track listing will create an initial implicit row track as 100 pixels and a second as `200px`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] This will continue for as long as content is added to the implicit grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] You can also ask grid to auto-place items by column.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Using the property `grid-auto-flow` with a value of `column`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In this case grid will add items in rows that you have defined using `grid-template-rows`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] When it fills up a column it will move onto the next explicit column, or create a new column track in the implicit grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] As with implicit row tracks, these column tracks will be auto sized.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] You can control the size of implicit column tracks with `grid-auto-columns`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] This works in the same way as `grid-auto-rows`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In this example, we have a grid with three 200px high row tracks.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] We declare `grid-auto-flow: column;` to auto-place by column.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] With `grid-auto-columns: 300px 100px;`, the columns created will alternate between being `300px` wide and `100px` wide until there are enough column tracks to hold all of the items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] A grid can contain a mixture of item placements.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Some of the items may have a specifically defined position on the grid, while others may be auto-placed.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] If you have a document order that reflects the order in which items sit on the grid, you may not need to write CSS rules to place absolutely everything.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The specification contains a long section detailing the Grid item placement algorithm; however, for most of us, we just need to remember a few rules for our items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Grid places items that have not been given a grid position in what is described in the specification as "order modified document order".
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] This means that if you have used the `order` property at all, the items will be placed by that order, not their DOM order.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Otherwise they will stay by default in the order that they are entered in the document source.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The first thing grid will do is place any items that have a position.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In the example below I have 12 grid items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Item 2 and item 5 have been placed using line based placement on the grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] You can see how those items are placed and the other items then auto-place in the spaces.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The auto-placed items will place themselves before the placed items in DOM order, they don't start after the position of a placed item that comes before them.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] You can use placement properties while still taking advantage of auto-placement.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In this next example I have added to the layout by setting items 1, 5, and 9 (4n+1) to span two tracks both for rows and columns.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] I do this with the `grid-column-end` and `grid-row-end` properties and setting the value of this to `span 2`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] What this means is that the start line of the item will be set by auto-placement, and the end line will span two tracks.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] You can see how this then leaves gaps in the grid, as for the auto-placed items if grid comes across an item that doesn't fit into a track, it will move to the next row until it finds a space the item can fit in.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] So far, other than items we have specifically placed, grid is always progressing forward and keeping items in DOM order.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] This is generally what you want, if you are laying out a form for example you wouldn't want the labels and fields to become jumbled up in order to fill in some gap.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] However sometimes, we are laying things out that don't have a logical order and we would like to create a layout that doesn't have gaps in it.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] To do this, add the property `grid-auto-flow` with a value of `dense` to the container.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] This is the same property you use to change the flow order to `column`, so if you were working in columns you would add both values `grid-auto-flow: column dense`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Having done this, grid will now backfill the gaps, as it moves through the grid it leaves gaps as before, but then if it finds an item that will fit in a previous gap it will pick it up and take it out of DOM order to place it in the gap.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] As with any other reordering in grid this does not change the logical order.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Tab order for example, will still follow the document order.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] We will take a look at the potential accessibility issues of grid layout in the Grid layout and accessibility guide, but you should take care when creating this disconnect between the visual order and display order.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] There is a mention in the specification of anonymous grid items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] These are created if you have a string of text inside your grid container, that is not wrapped in any other element.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In the example below we have three grid items, assuming you had set the parent with a class of `grid` to `display: grid`.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The first is an anonymous item as it has no enclosing markup, this item will always be dealt with via the auto-placement rules.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] The other two are grid items enclosed in a div, they might be auto-placed or you could place these with a positioning method onto your grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Anonymous items are always auto-placed because there is no way to target them.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Therefore if you have some unwrapped text for some reason in your grid, be aware that it might show up somewhere unexpected as it will be auto-placed according to the auto-placement rules.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Auto-placement is useful whenever you have a collection of items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] That could be items that do not have a logical order such as a gallery of photos, or product listing.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In that case you might choose to use the dense packing mode to fill in any holes in your grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In my image gallery example I have some landscape and some portrait images.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] I have set landscape images – with a class of `landscape` to span two column tracks.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] I then use `grid-auto-flow: dense` to create a densely packed grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Try removing the line `grid-auto-flow: dense` to see the content reflow to leave gaps in the layout.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Auto-placement can also help you lay out interface items which do have logical order.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] An example is the definition list in this next example.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Definition lists are an interesting challenge to style as they are flat, there is nothing wrapping the groups of `dt` and `dd` items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] In my example I am allowing auto-placement to place the items, however I have classes that start a `dt` in column 1, and `dd` in column 2, this ensure that terms go on one side and definitions on the other - no matter how many of each we have.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] There are a couple of things that often come up as questions.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] Currently we can't do things like target every other cell of the grid with our items.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] A related issue may have already come to mind if you followed the last guide about named lines on the grid.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] It would be to define a rule that said "auto-place items against the next line named "n", and grid would then skip other lines.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] There is an issue raised about this on the CSSWG GitHub repository, and you would be welcome to add your own use cases to this.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] It may be that you come up with your own use cases for auto-placement or any other part of grid layout.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] If you do, raise them as issues or add to an existing issue that could solve your use case.
[src:css-grid/auto-placement-in-grid-layout] This will help to make future versions of the specification better.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] CSS grid layout introduces a two-dimensional grid system to CSS.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grids can be used to lay out major page areas or small user interface elements.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This guide introduces the CSS grid layout and the terminology that is part of the CSS grid layout specification.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The features shown in this overview will then be explained in greater detail in the other guides in this series.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A grid is a set of intersecting horizontal and vertical lines defining rows and columns.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Elements can be placed onto the grid within these column and row lines.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can create a grid with fixed track sizes – using pixels for example.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This sets the grid to the specified pixel which fits to the layout you desire.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can also create a grid using flexible sizes with percentages or with the `fr` unit designed for this purpose.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can place items into a precise location on the grid using line numbers, names or by targeting an area of the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid also contains an algorithm to control the placement of items not given an explicit position on the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can define an explicit grid with grid layout.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The features defined by the grid layout module provide the flexibility to add additional rows and columns when needed.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Features such as adding "as many columns that will fit into a container" are included.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] CSS grid layout and CSS box alignment features enable us to control how the items align once placed into a grid area, and how the entire grid is aligned.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] More than one item can be placed into a grid cell or area and they can partially overlap each other.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This layering may then be controlled with the `z-index` property.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid is a powerful layout method that, when combined with other parts of CSS such as flexbox, can help you create layouts that are responsive, flexible, and accessible.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It all starts by creating a grid in your **grid container**.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We create a *grid container* by declaring `display: grid` or `display: inline-grid` on an element.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As soon as we do this, all *direct children* of that element become *grid items*.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we have a containing div with a class of `wrapper`.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We make the `.wrapper` a grid container using `display: grid;`.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] All the direct children are now grid items.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In a web browser, you won't see any difference to how these items are displayed before turning them into a grid, as grid has created a single column grid for the items.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If you inspect the grid in your browsers developer tools, you may see a small icon next to the value `grid`.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Click this and, in most browsers, the grid on this element will be overlaid in the browser window.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As you learn and then work with the CSS grid layout, your browser tools will give you a better idea of what is happening with your grids visually.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we want to start making this more grid-like we need to add column tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We define rows and columns on our grid with the `grid-template-rows` and `grid-template-columns` properties.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A *grid track* is the space between any two adjacent lines on the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The image below shows a highlighted track – this is the first-row track in our grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid tracks are defined in the explicit grid by using the `grid-template-columns` and `grid-template-rows` properties or the shorthand `grid` or `grid-template` properties.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Tracks are also created in the implicit grid by positioning a grid item outside of the tracks created in the explicit grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We can add column tracks to our earlier example by adding the `grid-template-columns` property, then defining the size of the column tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We have now created a grid with three 200-pixel-wide column tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The child items will be laid out on this grid one in each grid cell.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Tracks can be defined using any length unit.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid also introduces an additional length unit to help us create flexible grid tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The `fr` unit represents a fraction of the available space in the grid container.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The next grid definition would create three equal width tracks that grow and shrink according to the available space.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we create a definition with a `2fr` track then two `1fr` tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Two parts are given to the first track and one part each to the next two tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this final example, we mix absolute sized tracks with `fr` units.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The first track is `500px`, so the fixed width is taken away from the available space.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The remaining space is divided into three and assigned in proportion to the two flexible tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Large grids with many tracks can use the `repeat()` notation, to repeat all or a section of the list of grid tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Repeat notation can be used for a part of the list of tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we create an 8-column grid; the initial track is `20px`, then a repeating section of 6 `1fr` tracks, and a final `20px` track.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Repeat notation (`repeat()`) uses the track listing to create a repeating pattern of tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, the grid will have 10 tracks; a `1fr` track is followed by a `2fr` track, with this pattern being repeated five times.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] When creating our example grid, we specifically defined our column tracks with the `grid-template-columns` property, with the grid creating rows as needed to fit the content.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The columns define the explicit grid while the rows are part of the implicit grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The *explicit grid* consists of rows and columns defined with `grid-template-columns` or `grid-template-rows`.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The *implicit grid* extends the defined explicit grid when content is placed outside of that grid, such as into the rows by drawing additional grid lines.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If you place something outside of the defined grid or, due to the amount of content, more grid tracks are needed, then the grid creates rows and columns in the *implicit grid*.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] These implicit tracks are auto-sized by default, meaning the size of the created rows or columns is influenced by both their content and by the available free space within the grid container.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The `auto` keyword allows the generated tracks to accommodate content while also sharing any remaining space.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can also define a set size for tracks created in the implicit grid with the `grid-auto-rows` and `grid-auto-columns` properties.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we set `grid-auto-rows: 200px`, ensuring the tracks created in this implicit grid are `200px` tall.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] When setting up an explicit grid or defining the sizing for automatically created rows or columns we may want to give tracks a minimum size, but also ensure they expand to fit any content that is added.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] For example, we may want our rows to never collapse smaller than 100 pixels, but if our content stretches to 300 pixels in height, then we would like the row to stretch to that height.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This is solved by the `minmax()` function.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we use `minmax()` within the `grid-auto-rows` property value.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] By setting `grid-auto-rows: minmax(100px, auto);`, automatically created rows will be a minimum of `100px` tall, and have a maximum of `auto`.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Setting `auto` as the maximum value allows the track to grow to accommodate its content (up to its `max-content` size) while also sharing any available free space within the grid container.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It should be noted that when we define a grid we define the grid tracks, not the lines.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid then gives us numbered lines to use when positioning items.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In our three column, two row grid we have four column lines.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Lines are numbered according to the writing mode of the document.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In a left-to-right language, line 1 is on the left-hand side of the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In a right-to-left language, it is on the right-hand side of the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Lines can also be named, which is discussed in the grid layout using named grid lines guide.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The following example demonstrates basic line-based placement; when placing an item, we target the line rather than the track.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We explore this in greater detail in the grid layout using line-based placement guide.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, the first two items on our three column track grid are placed using the `grid-column-start`, `grid-column-end`, `grid-row-start` and `grid-row-end` properties.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Working from left to right, the first item is placed against column line 1, and spans to column line 4, which in our case is the far-right line on the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It begins at row line 1 and ends at row line 3, therefore spanning two row tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The second item starts on grid column line 1, and spans one track.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This is the default, so we do not need to specify the end line.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It also spans two row tracks from row line 3 to row line 5.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The other items will place themselves into empty spaces on the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Use the grid inspector in your developer tools to see how the items are positioned against the lines of the grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The longhand values used above can be compressed onto one line for columns with the `grid-column` shorthand, and one line for rows with the `grid-row` shorthand.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The following example would give the same positioning as in the previous code, but with far less CSS.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The value before the forward slash character (`/`) is the start line, the value after the end line.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can omit the end value if the area only spans one track.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A *grid cell* is the smallest unit on a grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As we saw in our earlier examples, once a grid is defined as a parent the child items will lay themselves out in one cell each of the defined grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In the below image, the first cell of the grid is highlighted.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Items can span one or more cells both by row or by column, and this creates a *grid area*.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid areas must be rectangular – it isn't possible to create an L-shaped area for example.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The highlighted grid area spans two row and two column tracks.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Any space used by gaps will be accounted for before space is assigned to the flexible length `fr` tracks, and gaps act for sizing purposes like a regular grid track, however you cannot place anything into a gap.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In terms of line-based positioning, the gap acts like a thick, transparent line.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A grid item can become a grid container.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In the following example, we extend the three-column grid with two positioned items seen earlier, adding sub-items to the first grid item.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As these nested items are not direct children of the grid they do not participate in grid layout and so display in a normal document flow.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we set `box1` to `display: grid`, we can give it a track definition and it too will become a grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The items then lay out on this new grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this case the nested grid has no relationship to the parent.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As you can see in the example it has not inherited the `gap` of the parent and the lines in the nested grid do not align to the lines in the parent grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In addition to regular grids, we can create *subgrid*.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The `subgrid` value lets us create nested grids that use the track definition of the parent grid.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] To use them, we edit the above nested grid example to change the track definition of `grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr)`, to `grid-template-columns: subgrid`.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The nested grid then uses the parent grid tracks to lay out items.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid items can occupy the same cell, and in this case we can use the `z-index` property to control the order in which overlapping items stack.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we return to our example with items positioned by line number, we can change this to make two items overlap.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The item `box2` is now overlapping `box1`, it displays on top as it comes later in the source order.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We can control the order in which items stack up by using the `z-index` property - just like positioned items.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we give `box2` a lower `z-index` than `box1` it will display below `box1` in the stack.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this overview, we took a very quick look at the possibilities of grid layouts.
[src:css-grid/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Explore and play with the code examples, and then move on to the guide, relationship of grid layout with other layout methods, where we will really start to dig into the details of CSS grid layout.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] It’s been available across browsers since October 2017.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The **`gap`** CSS shorthand property sets the gaps (also called gutters) between rows and columns on multi-column, flex, and grid containers.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The `gap` property defines gaps between columns and rows, with the effect of the definition depending on whether the container is a grid container, a flexbox container, or a multi-column layout container.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The shorthand property is specified as a value for `<'row-gap'>`, followed optionally by a value for `<'column-gap'>`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] While the default value is `normal` for both sub-properties, if only one value is declared, that value applies to both.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Both `<'row-gap'>` and `<'column-gap'>` can each be specified as a `<length>`, a `<percentage>`, or the keyword `normal`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Percentage gap values are always calculated against the content box size of the container element.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The behavior is well-defined and consistent across layout modes when the container size is definite.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The generated gaps create empty spaces that have the width or height of the gap's specified size, much like an empty item or track.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The visible space between elements may differ from the provided `gap` value because margins, padding, and distributed alignment may increase the separation between elements beyond what is determined by `gap`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Gaps may contain visible separators as gap decorations.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] If there are decorative rules between the columns, rows, or both, they will appear in the middle of their gap, but have no effect on the gaps' size.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] These decorative lines can be added to the otherwise "empty space" by using the `rule` shorthand.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] In CSS grid layout, the `gap` property defines the space between rows and columns.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The first value defines the gutter between rows, and the second defines the gutter between columns.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] If only one value is included, that value is used for both dimensions.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Percentage values are calculated against the content box size of the container element.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Cyclic percentage sizes resolve against zero for determining intrinsic size contributions but resolve against the grid container's content box when laying out the contents.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Two examples below demonstrate percentage gap values with explicit container size and implicit container size in the examples section.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The effect of positive `gap` values is as though the grid lines acquired thickness: the grid track between two grid lines is the space between the gutters that represent them.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] If a grid item spans multiple rows or columns, for the purpose of track sizing, the gutter is treated as an extra, empty, fixed-size track of the specified size, added to the dimension in the spanning direction.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] For example, if `gap: 10px` is set on a 3x3 grid of 100px by 100px boxes, if a grid item spans two vertical columns, it's width would be `210px`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] If it spans all three, it has a width of `320px`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The space between grid rows and columns may be larger than the value of the `gap` property due to space added between tracks by the `justify-content` and `align-content` properties.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Gutters only appear between tracks of the implicit grid.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] If a grid is fragmented between tracks, no gutter spacing is added between those tracks.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] There is no gutter before the first track or after the last track, and if a track is collapsed, it will have no gutter.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Early versions of the CSS grid specification called this property `grid-gap`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] To maintain compatibility with legacy websites, browsers accept `grid-gap` as an alias for `gap`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] With flex containers, the `gap` property defines the space between both flex items and flex lines.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Whether the first value is the gap between flex items or between flex lines depends on the direction.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Flex items are laid out in either rows or columns depending on the value of the `flex-direction` property.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] For rows (`row` (the default) or `row-reverse`), the first value defines the gap between flex lines, and the second value defines the gap between items within each line.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] For columns (`column` or `column-reverse`), the first value defines the gap between flex items within a flex line, and the second value defines the gaps between each flex line.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Again, if only one value is included, that value is used for both dimensions.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] In CSS multi-column layout, the property defines the gutter between columns and rows of columns.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The first value defines the gap between adjacent column boxes, while the second value defines the size of the gutter between rows of column boxes, if multiple rows were established by the `column-height` property.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] If the container has a fixed size set, then gap percentage value calculations are based on the size of the container.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Thus, gap behavior is consistent across all layouts.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] In the following example, there are two containers, one with a grid layout and the other with a flex layout.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The containers have five red 20x20px children.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Both containers are explicitly set to 200px high using `height: 200px` and the gap is set with `gap: 12.5% 0`.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Now inspect the grid and flex elements using Inspector tab in Web Developer Tools.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] In order to see the actual gaps hover mouse over `<div id="grid">` and `<div id="flex">` tags in the inspector.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] You will notice that the gap is the same in both cases which is 25px.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] If size is not explicitly set on the container, then the percentage gap behaves differently in case of grid and flex layouts.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] In the following example the containers don't have height explicitly set.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] In case of the grid layout, percentage gap doesn't contribute to the actual height of the grid.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The container's height is calculated using `0px` gap, so the actual height turns out to be 100px (20px x 5).
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Then the actual percentage gap is calculated using the content box's height, the gap turns out to be `12.5px` (100px x 12.5%).
[src:css-grid/css-gap] The gap is applied just before rendering.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] Thus the grid remains 100px high but it overflows due to the percentage gap added later just before rendering.
[src:css-grid/css-gap] In case of the flex layout, the percentage gap always results in zero value.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] The **CSS grid layout** module excels at dividing a page into major regions or defining the relationship in terms of size, position, and layering between parts of a control built from HTML primitives.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] Like tables, grid layout enables an author to align elements into columns and rows.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] However, many more layouts are either possible or easier with CSS grid than they were with tables.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] For example, a grid container's child elements could position themselves so they actually overlap and layer, similar to CSS positioned elements.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] The example shows a three-column track grid with new rows created at a minimum of 100 pixels and a maximum of auto.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] Items have been placed onto the grid using line-based placement.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] This sample animation uses `display`, `grid-template-columns`, `grid-template-rows`, and `gap` to create the grid, and `grid-column` and `grid-row` to position items within in the grid.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] To view and edit the HTML and CSS used, click the 'Play' at the top right of the example.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] An overview of the various features provided in the CSS grid layout module.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] How grid layout fits together with other CSS features including flexbox, absolutely positioned elements, and `display: contents`.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] Grid lines and how to position items against those lines, including the `grid-area` properties, negative line numbers, spanning multiple cells, and creating grid gutters.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] Placing grid items using named template areas.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] Combining names and track sizes; placing grid items by defining named grid lined and template areas.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] How grid positions items that don't have any placement properties declared.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] Aligning, justifying, and centering grid items along the two axes of a grid layout.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] A look at the interaction between CSS grid layout, box alignment and writing modes, along with CSS logical and physical properties and values.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] A look at how CSS grid layout can both help and harm accessibility.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] A few different layouts demonstrating different techniques you can use when designing with CSS grid layouts, including using `grid-template-areas`, a 12-column flexible grid system, and a product listing using auto-placement.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] What subgrid does with use cases and design patterns that subgrid solves.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] Details what masonry layout is and it is used.
[src:css-grid/css-grid-layout] How box alignment works in the context of grid layout.
[src:css-grid/css-grid] The **`grid`** CSS property is a shorthand property that sets all of the explicit and implicit grid properties in a single declaration.
[src:css-grid/css-grid] Using `grid` you specify one axis using `grid-template-rows` or `grid-template-columns`, you then specify how content should auto-repeat in the other axis using the implicit grid properties: `grid-auto-rows`, `grid-auto-columns`, and `grid-auto-flow`.
[src:css-grid/css-grid] Defines the `grid-template` including `grid-template-columns`, `grid-template-rows` and `grid-template-areas`.
[src:css-grid/css-grid] Sets up an auto-flow by setting the row tracks explicitly via the `grid-template-rows` property (and the `grid-template-columns` property to `none`) and specifying how to auto-repeat the column tracks via `grid-auto-columns` (and setting `grid-auto-rows` to `auto`).
[src:css-grid/css-grid] `grid-auto-flow` is also set to `column` accordingly, with `dense` if it's specified.
[src:css-grid/css-grid] All other `grid` sub-properties are reset to their initial values.
[src:css-grid/css-grid] Sets up an auto-flow by setting the column tracks explicitly via the `grid-template-columns` property (and the `grid-template-rows` property to `none`) and specifying how to auto-repeat the row tracks via `grid-auto-rows` (and setting `grid-auto-columns` to `auto`).
[src:css-grid/css-grid] `grid-auto-flow` is also set to `row` accordingly, with `dense` if it's specified.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] In graphic design, a **grid** is a structure (usually two-dimensional) made up of a series of intersecting straight (vertical, horizontal, and angular) or curved lines (**grid lines**) used to structure content.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The grid serves as an armature or framework on which a designer can organize graphic elements (images, glyphs, paragraphs, etc.) in a rational, easy-to-absorb manner.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] A grid can be used to organize graphic elements in relation to a page, in relation to other graphic elements on the page, or relation to other parts of the same graphic element or shape.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The less-common printing term "reference grid," is an unrelated system with roots in the early days of printing.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Before the invention of movable type a system based on optimal proportions had been used to arrange handwritten text on pages.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] One such system, known as the Villard Diagram, was in use at least since medieval times.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] After World War II, a number of graphic designers, including Max Bill, Emil Ruder, and Josef Müller-Brockmann, influenced by the modernist ideas of Jan Tschichold's *Die neue Typographie* (The New Typography), began to question the relevance of the conventional page layout of the time.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] They began to devise a flexible system able to help designers achieve coherency in organizing the page.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The result was the modern typographic grid that became associated with the International Typographic Style.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The seminal work on the subject, *Grid systems in graphic design* by Müller-Brockmann, helped propagate the use of the grid, first in Europe, and later in North America.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] By the mid-1970s instruction of the typographic grid as a part of graphic design curricula had become standard in Europe, North America and much of Latin America.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The graphic style of the grid was adopted as a look for corporate communication.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] In the early 1980s, a reaction against the entrenchment of the grid, particularly its dogmatic use, and association with corporate culture, resulted in some designers rejecting its use in favor of more organic structure.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The appearance of the Apple Macintosh computer, and the resulting transition away from type being set by typographers to designers setting type themselves resulted in a wave of experimentation, much of it contrary to the precepts of Tschichold and Müller-Brockmann.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The typographic grid continues to be taught today, but more as a useful tool for some projects, not as a requirement or starting point for all page design.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] While grid systems have seen significant use in print media, interest from web developers has only recently seen a resurgence.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Website design frameworks producing HTML and CSS had existed for a while before newer frameworks popularised the use of grid-based layouts.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Some grid systems specify fixed-width elements with pixels, and some are 'fluid', meaning that they call for page element sizing to be in relative units like percentages, rather than absolute units like pixels or points.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] The W3C published the CSS Grid Layout Module Level 1 to define a two-dimensional grid-based layout system.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Print design has always used grid systems to organize and structure content.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Grid systems started as helper lines for written books.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Artists used grid systems to layout the content – text and images – in a manner that makes reading and absorption easier.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Newspapers, books, magazines, and classifieds, etc., all use different grid systems that make the optimum use of space for better reading and presentation.
[src:css-grid/grid-graphic-design] Most desktop publishing software and professional publishing software and other office software including word processors displays grid layout as an option.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] The **`grid-template-columns`** CSS property defines the line names and track sizing functions of the grid columns.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Indicates that there is no explicit grid.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Any columns will be implicitly generated and their size will be determined by the `grid-auto-columns` property.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] A `<custom-ident>` specifying a name for the line in that location.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] The ident may be any valid string other than the reserved words `span` and `auto`.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Lines may have multiple names separated by a space inside the square brackets, for example `[line-name-a line-name-b]`.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] A non-negative length, giving the width of the column.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] A non-negative `<percentage>` value relative to the inline size of the grid container.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] If the size of the grid container depends on the size of its tracks, the browser treats the percentage as `auto`.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] The browser may adjust the intrinsic size contributions of the track to the size of the grid container and may increase the final size of the track by the minimum amount that would result in honoring the percentage.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Is a non-negative dimension with the unit `fr` specifying the track's flex factor.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Each `<flex>`-sized track takes a share of the remaining space in proportion to its flex factor.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] When appearing outside a `minmax()` notation, it implies an automatic minimum (i.e., `minmax(auto, <flex>)`).
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Is a keyword representing the largest maximal content contribution of the grid items occupying the grid track.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Is a keyword representing the largest minimal content contribution of the grid items occupying the grid track.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Is a functional notation that defines a size range greater than or equal to *min* and less than or equal to *max*.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] If *max* is smaller than *min*, then *max* is ignored and the function is treated as *min*.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] As a maximum, a `<flex>` value sets the track's flex factor.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] As a maximum value, it represents the largest `max-content` size of the items in that track.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] As a minimum value, it represents the largest minimum size of items in that track (specified by the `min-width`/`min-height` properties of the items).
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] This often corresponds to the `min-content` size, but not always.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] If used outside of `minmax()` notation, `auto` represents the range between the minimum and maximum values described above.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] In most cases, this behaves similarly to `minmax(min-content,max-content)`.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Represents the formula `max(minimum, min(limit, max-content))`, where *minimum* represents an `auto` minimum (which is often, but not always, equal to a `min-content` minimum), and *limit* is the track sizing function passed as an argument to fit-content().
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] This is essentially calculated as the smaller of `minmax(auto, max-content)` and `minmax(auto, limit)`.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Represents a repeated fragment of the track list, allowing a large number of columns that exhibit a recurring pattern to be written in a more compact form.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] The masonry value indicates that this axis should be laid out according to the masonry algorithm.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] The `subgrid` value indicates that the grid will adopt the spanned portion of its parent grid in that axis.
[src:css-grid/grid-template-columns] Rather than being specified explicitly, the sizes of the grid rows/columns will be taken from the parent grid's definition.
